data_1 <- read_excel("CMO-Historical-Data-Monthly.xlsx", sheet = "Monthly Prices", skip = 4) %>%
  mutate(
    `Coal, Australian` = as.numeric(`Coal, Australian **`),
    `Coal, South African` = as.numeric(`Coal, South African **`)
  ) %>% 
  select(`Coal, Australian`, `Coal, South African`) %>% 
  filter( !is.na(`Coal, South African`)) %>% 
  mutate(date = seq(as.Date("1984-01-01"), length = 468, by = "month"))
data_1 <- data_1 %>% 
  mutate(Date = yearmonth(date))

data_1_tsb <- data_1 %>% 
  as_tsibble(index = Date) 

#lets separate 10 observations

data_2_tsb <- data_1_tsb[1:(nrow(data_1_tsb)-10),]

data_au_ts <- data_2_tsb %>% 
  select(., `Coal, Australian`, Date)

data_saf_ts <- data_2_tsb %>% 
  select(., `Coal, South African`, Date)

Model fit

fit_au <- data_au_ts %>% 
  model(arima110_au = ARIMA(`Coal, Australian` ~ pdq(1,1,0)+ PDQ(0,0,0)), 
        arima210_au = ARIMA(`Coal, Australian` ~ pdq(2,1,0)+ PDQ(0,0,0)),
        arima111_au = ARIMA(`Coal, Australian` ~ pdq(1,1,1)+ PDQ(0,0,0)),
        arima511_au = ARIMA(`Coal, Australian` ~ PDQ(0,0,0), stepwise = FALSE, greedy = FALSE))

Experts forecast:

The last World Bank forecast of commodity market prices was made at October 2022. The price on Australian coal forecasted by the experts in October 2022 for 2023 is USD 240, whereas the price forecasted by our model is USD 382.9610681. The prices are inconsistent with each other. The reason is the caused by war structural break in our data that occurred in November 2022 and was not included to the training sample of experts at World Bank who did the forecast in October 2022 (as they used data before Feb 2022). However, the actual price for Australian coal was USD 317.99 in Jan 2023, and the forecast for Jan 2023 is 380.24. Conclusion: including all data up to end of 2022 increases accuracy of the model but still there is difference of -62.25 between actual and forecasted value for Jan 2023.

Part II

Table of contents for the second part: - Check for ARCH effect in our data - plot graphs of ACF, PACF, residuals and squared residuals - Select the needed parameters for our model (both for AU and SAF) - Complete tests to see of our models are satisfactory - Recomplete forecast and plot results

Check for ARCH effect in our data:

As well as we selected arima111 for both categories of prices, we will proceed with this specification. Just for the report not to take 1000+ lines of codes, we will stick only to a AU coal prices keeping in mind that the same procedure could be done for SAF prices on coal as well. However, as well as we cannot get residuals of forecasted models, we will use our models on our whole data

For AU:

Lets check that visually

Model creation:

arima_au_111 <- arima(data_au_ts_fore2023$`Coal, Australian`, order = c(1,1,1))

resid_au <- arima_au_111$residuals
resid_au_sq <- resid_au^2

ACF:

ggAcf(resid_au)

PACF:

ggPacf(resid_au)

Even if that is negotiable somehow, the next graphs will deal with all the debates.

ACF for squared residuals:

ggAcf(resid_au_sq)

PACF for squared residuals:

ggPacf(resid_au_sq)

As we can see, there is an autocorrelation function on acf and pacf that we can get from residuals squared.

One more proof:

resid_au %>% autoplot()

For sure ARCH exists. Lets prove that formally.

lag_au <- as.integer(round(log(nrow(data_au_ts_fore2023)),0))
FinTS::ArchTest(residuals(arima_au_111), lags=lag_au)
## 
##  ARCH LM-test; Null hypothesis: no ARCH effects
## 
## data:  residuals(arima_au_111)
## Chi-squared = 126.42, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

Result: low p-value. ARCH exists. Lets deal with it.

We will try to evaluate what we have on the following models: GARCH(1,1), ARCH(2), ARCH(1). But, as stated by our TA and by the same statement from the book, GARCH(1,1) actually can catch high autoregressive orders, so we will not use any ARCH(3)+.

As well as GARCH model do not work with differenced models, we need to settle our data already differenced.

data_au_ts_fore2023_copy <- data_au_ts_fore2023
data_au_ts_fore2023_copy$au_price_diff <- NA
view(data_au_ts_fore2023_copy)

for (i in (2:(nrow(data_au_ts_fore2023_copy)))) {
  data_au_ts_fore2023_copy$au_price_diff[i] <- data_au_ts_fore2023_copy$`Coal, Australian`[i] - data_au_ts_fore2023_copy$`Coal, Australian`[i-1]
}

data_au_ts_fore2023_copy$au_price_diff[1] <- 0

data_au_test <- data_au_ts_fore2023_copy[1:(nrow(data_au_ts_fore2023_copy)-10),]
data_au_check <- data_au_ts_fore2023_copy[(nrow(data_au_ts_fore2023_copy)-9):nrow(data_au_ts_fore2023_copy),]

GARCH(1,1)

garch1_1Spec_au = ugarchspec(variance.model=list(model="sGARCH", garchOrder=c(1,1)),
              mean.model=list(armaOrder=c(1,1),
              include.mean=T))

garch1_1Fit_au <- ugarchfit(spec = garch1_1Spec_au, data = data_au_test$au_price_diff)
print(garch1_1Fit_au)

forecast_garch_au <- ugarchboot(garch1_1Fit_au, method = c("Partial","Full")[1],
                            n.ahead = 10, n.bootpred = 1000, n.bootfit = 1000)

sigma_au <- forecast_garch_au@forc@forecast$sigmaFor[1]
high_au <- f_garch_au + 1.96*sigma_au
low_au <- f_garch_au - 1.96*sigma_au
